05329nam a22007695i 9780226665641DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20202020ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2019032051  a9780226665641  a(DE-B1597)545022  a(OCoLC)1143619518  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aHC110.I5bK45 2019 4aHC110.I5bK45 2020 7aPOL0000002bisacsh04a339.2209732231 aKelly, Nathan J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAmerica's Inequality Trap /cNathan J. Kelly. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (232 p.) :b34 line drawings, 11 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aChicago Studies in American Politics00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tONE. Contemporary Politics and the Perpetuation of Inequality -- tTWO. An Inescapable Plutocracy? -- tTHREE. Public Preferences and Economic Inequality -- tFOUR. Elections and the Inequality Trap -- tFIVE. Partisan Convergence and Financial Deregulation -- tSIX. Polarization and Policy Stagnation -- tSEVEN. Can We Escape the Trap? -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tNOTES -- tREFERENCES -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe gap between the rich and the poor has grown dramatically in the United States and is now at its widest since at least the early 1900s. While by most measures the economy has been improving, soaring cost of living and stagnant wages have done little to assuage economic anxieties. Conditions like these seem designed to produce a generation-defining intervention to balance the economic scales and enhance opportunities for those at the middle and bottom of the country’s economic ladder—but we have seen nothing of the sort. Nathan J. Kelly argues that a key reason for this is that rising concentrations of wealth create a politics that makes reducing economic inequality more difficult. Kelly convincingly shows that, when a small fraction of the people control most of the economic resources, they also hold a disproportionate amount of political power, hurtling us toward a self-perpetuating plutocracy, or an “inequality trap.” Among other things, the rich support a broad political campaign that convinces voters that policies to reduce inequality are unwise and not in the average voter’s interest, regardless of the real economic impact. They also take advantage of interest groups they generously support to influence Congress and the president, as well as state governments, in ways that stop or slow down reform. One of the key implications of this book is that social policies designed to combat inequality should work hand-in-hand with political reforms that enhance democratic governance and efforts to fight racism, and a coordinated effort on all of these fronts will be needed to reverse the decades-long trend.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aElectionsxEconomic aspectszUnited States. 0aElectionszUnited StatesxEconomic aspects. 0aEqualityxPolitical aspectszUnited States. 0aIncome distributionxPolitical aspectszUnited States. 0aWealthxPolitical aspectszUnited States. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aelections.  ainequality.  apolicy making.  apolitical behavior.  apolitical economy.  apolitical institutions.  apower.  apublic opinion.  aredistribution.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Political Science 2020z9783110704594oZDB-23-PLW08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Social Sciences 2020 Englishz9783110